VALUES
(44, 16, 13, 44, 13, 14, 14, 'on the sabbath', 'Sabbath Observance in Acts', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the sabbath day as a time for gathering and prayer. Acts 16:13 mentions going out by the river for prayer, while Acts 13:14 highlights entering the synagogue on the sabbath.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 13, 51, 1, 23, 23, 'prayer was wont to be made', 'Faith and Gospel Connection', 'This connection highlights the importance of faith and prayer in the early Christian community. Both passages emphasize the need to remain steadfast in faith and the role of the gospel in shaping that faith.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 13, 40, 5, 1, 2, NULL, 'Teaching and Gathering for Prayer', 'This connection highlights the act of gathering for teaching and prayer. Both passages depict a setting where individuals come together to receive instruction and engage in spiritual practices.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 13, 40, 13, 2, 2, NULL, 'Gathering for Prayer and Teaching', 'This connection highlights the act of gathering for spiritual purposes. Both passages depict groups coming together, whether for prayer by the river or to hear teachings by Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 13, 41, 16, 15, 15, 'prayer was wont to be made', 'Connection of Mission and Prayer', 'This connection highlights the theme of outreach and prayer. In Acts, the gathering for prayer precedes the mission to share the gospel, as emphasized in Mark''s call to preach to all. Both passages emphasize the importance of preparation through prayer for the mission.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 13, 42, 4, 20, 21, 'where prayer was wont to be made', 'Connection of Prayer and Fulfillment', 'This connection highlights the act of gathering for prayer and the significance of fulfillment in scripture. Both passages emphasize communal engagement with faith, as seen in the women praying and Jesus proclaiming the fulfillment of prophecy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 13, 42, 13, 10, 10, 'on the sabbath', 'Sabbath Observance in Teaching', 'Both passages emphasize activities occurring on the sabbath. Acts 16:13 mentions prayer on the sabbath, while Luke 13:10 highlights teaching in a synagogue on the same day.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 14, 42, 24, 45, 45, 'whose heart the Lord opened', 'Understanding and Openness', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine enlightenment in both passages. In Acts, Lydia''s heart is opened to Paul''s message, while in Luke, Jesus opens understanding to the scriptures.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 14, 49, 1, 17, 18, 'whose heart the Lord opened', 'Connection of Enlightenment and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine enlightenment. In Acts, Lydia''s heart was opened by the Lord, paralleling Ephesians where the eyes of understanding are enlightened.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 14, 23, 50, 5, 5, 'the Lord opened', 'Opening of the Heart and Ear', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine openness in both passages. Lydia''s heart is opened by the Lord, paralleling the opening of the ear in Isaiah, suggesting receptiveness to God''s message.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 14, 43, 6, 44, 45, 'whose heart the Lord opened', 'Divine Drawing and Understanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine action in drawing individuals to God. In Acts, Lydia''s heart is opened by the Lord, paralleling John’s assertion that the Father draws people to Jesus.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 14, 66, 3, 20, 20, 'whose heart the Lord opened', 'Opening Hearts and Doors', 'This connection highlights the theme of receptivity to divine invitation. Lydia''s heart was opened to Paul''s message, paralleling the call to open the door to Christ''s presence in Revelation.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 14, 47, 3, 14, 16, 'whose heart the Lord opened', 'Heart and Understanding Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of the heart''s openness to understanding spiritual truths. In Acts, Lydia''s heart is opened by the Lord, enabling her to attend to Paul''s message, while in 2 Corinthians, the vail upon the heart symbolizes a lack of understanding that is removed when one turns to the Lord.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 14, 45, 9, 16, 16, 'whose heart the Lord opened', 'Divine Influence on Belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine action in belief. In Acts, Lydia''s heart is opened by God, while Romans emphasizes that mercy is shown by God, not by human effort.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 15, 44, 11, 14, 14, NULL, 'Salvation and Household Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of a household in relation to faith and salvation. In Acts 11:14, the promise of salvation extends to the household, while Acts 16:15 shows a household being baptized, highlighting the communal aspect of faith.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 15, 58, 13, 2, 2, 'come into my house, and abide there', 'Hospitality and Faithfulness', 'This connection highlights the theme of hospitality, as both passages emphasize the importance of welcoming others. In Acts 16:15, the act of inviting the apostles into her house reflects a faithful response to their ministry, while Hebrews 13:2 encourages entertaining strangers, suggesting that such acts may have deeper significance.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 15, 44, 16, 33, 33, NULL, 'Baptism and Household Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of baptism involving entire households. Both passages emphasize the immediate baptism of individuals and their families, showcasing a communal aspect of faith.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 15, 1, 19, 3, 3, 'come into my house', 'Hospitality and Invitation', 'Both passages emphasize the act of inviting others into one''s home. In Acts, Lydia constrains the apostles to stay, while in Genesis, Lot presses the visitors to enter his house.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 15, 42, 24, 29, 29, 'abide there', 'Invitation to Abide', 'Both passages emphasize the act of inviting others to stay or abide with them. In Acts, Lydia invites Paul and his companions into her house, while in Luke, the disciples urge Jesus to abide with them as evening approaches.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 15, 46, 1, 13, 16, 'her household', 'Baptism and Household Connections', 'This connection highlights the significance of baptism within households. Both passages emphasize the act of baptizing individuals and their families, illustrating the communal aspect of faith in early Christianity.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 15, 57, 1, 17, 17, 'come into my house, and abide there', 'Hospitality and Partnership', 'This connection highlights the theme of hospitality and partnership in both passages. In Acts 16:15, the act of inviting others into one''s home reflects a welcoming spirit, which parallels the call in Philemon 1:17 to receive someone as a partner.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 16, 3, 19, 31, 31, 'spirit of divination', 'Connection Between Divination and Familiar Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of spirits associated with divination and the prohibition against seeking them. Acts 16:16 describes a girl with a spirit of divination, while Leviticus 19:31 warns against familiar spirits, highlighting a consistent biblical theme of caution against such practices.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 16, 5, 18, 9, 11, 'spirit of divination', 'Divination and Forbidden Practices', 'Both passages emphasize the practice of divination, which is condemned in Deuteronomy. The damsel in Acts is described as possessing a spirit of divination, linking her to the abominations mentioned in Deuteronomy.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 16, 23, 8, 19, 19, 'spirit of divination', 'Divination and Seeking God', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking spiritual guidance. Both passages address the issue of seeking out spirits or divination instead of turning to God for wisdom.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 16, 9, 28, 7, 7, 'spirit of divination', 'Connection of Divination Practices', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of individuals involved in divination. The damsel in Acts is described as possessing a spirit of divination, while Saul seeks a woman with a familiar spirit, indicating a thematic link between the two forms of supernatural inquiry.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 16, 13, 10, 13, 13, 'spirit of divination', 'Connection of Divination and Familiar Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of spirits associated with divination. Acts 16:16 mentions a spirit of divination, while 1 Chronicles 10:13 refers to a familiar spirit, illustrating a thematic link between seeking counsel from supernatural sources.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 16, 48, 5, 20, 20, 'spirit of divination', 'Connection of Divination and Witchcraft', 'This connection highlights the theme of witchcraft and divination as practices condemned in scripture. Both passages emphasize the negative implications of such spiritual practices.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 16, 54, 6, 10, 10, 'much gain by soothsaying', 'Connection of Money and Sorrows', 'This connection highlights the theme of profit and its consequences. In Acts, the damsel''s spirit of divination brings gain, while 1 Timothy warns that the love of money leads to sorrows.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 17, 43, 14, 6, 6, 'the way of salvation', 'Connection of Salvation and Way', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''the way'' leading to salvation. In Acts, the servant identifies Paul as showing ''the way of salvation,'' while in John, Jesus declares Himself as ''the way.''', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 17, 60, 2, 16, 16, 'servants of the most high God', 'Servants of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the role of believers as ''servants of God.'' Acts 16:17 identifies Paul and his companions as servants proclaiming salvation, while 1 Peter 2:16 encourages believers to act as servants, using their freedom responsibly.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 17, 41, 5, 7, 7, 'most high God', 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''most high God,'' highlighting a recognition of divine authority. This connection showcases the acknowledgment of God''s power by different entities in the narrative.', 'keyword', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 17, 27, 6, 20, 20, 'servants of the most high God', 'Servants of God Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of the characters as servants of God. In Acts, Paul is identified as a servant of the most high God, while in Daniel, Daniel is referred to as a servant of the living God.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 17, 27, 3, 26, 26, 'servants of the most high God', 'Servants of the Most High God', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''servants of the most high God,'' linking the identity of Paul and his companions with Shadrach, Meshach, and Abed-nego. This connection highlights the recognition of divine authority and the role of God''s servants in delivering messages of salvation and deliverance.', 'keyword', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 17, 19, 57, 2, 2, 'most high God', 'Connection of Divine Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''most high God.'' Acts 16:17 identifies Paul as a servant of the most high God, while Psalms 57:2 addresses God most high directly, highlighting His authority and role in salvation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 17, 32, 1, 9, 9, 'servants of the most high God', 'Servants of God and Fear', 'This connection highlights the acknowledgment of God’s authority in both passages. In Acts, the declaration of Paul as ''servants of the most high God'' parallels Jonah''s identification of himself as one who ''fears the Lord.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 18, 41, 16, 17, 17, 'I command thee in the name of Jesus Christ', 'Casting Out Spirits Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the authority to cast out spirits in the name of Jesus. Acts 16:18 demonstrates this power in action, while Mark 16:17 outlines it as a sign for believers.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 18, 42, 10, 17, 19, 'in the name of Jesus Christ', 'Authority Over Evil Spirits', 'This connection highlights the authority given to believers over evil spirits. Both passages emphasize the power of Jesus'' name in commanding spirits and overcoming the enemy.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 18, 41, 1, 34, 34, NULL, 'Exorcism and Healing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of casting out devils. In Acts, Paul commands a spirit to leave, while in Mark, Jesus casts out many devils, highlighting a shared theme of authority over evil spirits.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 18, 44, 3, 6, 6, 'in the name of Jesus Christ', 'Healing in Jesus'' Name', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of Jesus'' name in performing miraculous healings. In Acts 16:18, Paul commands a spirit to leave in Jesus'' name, while in Acts 3:6, Peter heals a man using the same authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 18, 44, 9, 34, 34, 'in the name of Jesus Christ', 'Healing in the Name of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the power of Jesus'' name in healing. In Acts 16:18, Paul commands a spirit to leave in Jesus'' name, while in Acts 9:34, Peter declares Jesus makes Eneas whole.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 18, 51, 2, 15, 15, 'I command thee in the name of Jesus Christ', 'Victory Over Spiritual Forces', 'This connection highlights the theme of triumph over spiritual powers. In Acts 16:18, Paul commands a spirit to come out, demonstrating authority over evil. Similarly, Colossians 2:15 speaks of Christ triumphing over principalities and powers, emphasizing victory over spiritual opposition.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 18, 42, 9, 1, 1, NULL, 'Authority Over Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the power and authority given to believers over evil spirits. In Acts, Paul commands a spirit to come out, while in Luke, Jesus gives his disciples authority over devils.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 19, 44, 17, 6, 6, 'drew them into the marketplace', 'Opposition to Paul and Silas', 'This connection highlights the theme of opposition faced by Paul and Silas due to their actions. In both passages, individuals are drawn to the rulers, indicating a response to the disruption caused by their ministry.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 19, 44, 21, 30, 30, 'drew them into the marketplace', 'Paul''s Arrest and Public Outcry', 'Both passages emphasize the public reaction to Paul being seized. In Acts 16:19, Paul is caught and drawn into the marketplace, while in Acts 21:30, he is drawn out of the temple amidst a tumultuous crowd.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 19, 47, 6, 5, 5, NULL, 'Suffering and Imprisonment Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the experience of suffering and imprisonment. Acts 16:19 describes Paul and Silas being caught and brought to the rulers, while 2 Corinthians 6:5 lists imprisonments as part of their hardships.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 19, 40, 24, 9, 9, NULL, 'Persecution for Faith', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering and persecution faced by believers. Both passages emphasize the consequences of faith, as Paul and Silas are caught and delivered up, paralleling the affliction mentioned in Matthew.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 19, 41, 13, 9, 9, NULL, 'Persecution of Paul and Silas', 'This connection highlights the theme of being brought before rulers due to faith. Both passages emphasize the experience of being delivered to authorities as a consequence of their actions for the sake of the Gospel.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 19, 40, 10, 16, 18, NULL, 'Persecution for Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the experience of being delivered up to authorities due to faith. Acts 16:19 illustrates the immediate consequences of preaching, while Matthew 10:16-18 warns of similar future persecutions faced by believers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 19, 59, 2, 6, 6, NULL, 'Oppression and Judgment Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of oppression, as both passages address the exploitation of individuals by those in power. In Acts, Paul and Silas are drawn before rulers due to the loss of profit for their masters, while James points out how rich men oppress the poor and bring them before judgment seats.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 20, 59, 4, 4, 4, 'trouble our city', 'Conflict with the World', 'This connection highlights the theme of opposition to worldly values. In Acts, the men trouble the city, reflecting a conflict with societal norms, while James warns against friendship with the world, indicating enmity with God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 20, 43, 15, 18, 20, 'trouble our city', 'Persecution of Believers', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by believers. Both passages emphasize that followers of Christ will experience hatred and trouble from the world, as seen in the treatment of Paul and Silas in Acts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 20, 44, 28, 22, 22, 'trouble our city', 'Opposition to the Early Church', 'This connection highlights the consistent opposition faced by the early Christians. Both passages emphasize how the followers of Jesus were seen as troubling or controversial figures in their communities.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 20, 45, 12, 2, 2, NULL, 'Transformation and Disturbance', 'This connection highlights the contrast between being troubled by the world and being transformed by God. Both passages emphasize the need for a change in mindset and behavior in the face of societal pressures.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 20, 11, 18, 17, 18, NULL, 'Troubling Influence in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals being accused of causing trouble. In both passages, the speakers attribute societal unrest to the actions of others, emphasizing the conflict between divine commandments and human actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 20, 15, 4, 12, 15, 'these men, being Jews, do exceedingly trouble our city', 'Accusations Against Jews', 'This connection highlights the theme of accusations against the Jews in both passages. In Acts, the Jews are said to ''trouble our city,'' while in Ezra, they are described as building a ''rebellious city'' that threatens the king''s revenue.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 20, 17, 3, 8, 9, 'these men, being Jews', 'Persecution of Jews Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the persecution of Jews. In Acts, the Jews are accused of troubling the city, while in Esther, Haman seeks to destroy them for their diverse laws.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 21, 17, 3, 8, 8, 'customs, which are not lawful for us', 'Laws and Customs of Different Peoples', 'Both passages emphasize the divergence of laws and customs between the Romans and the Jews. Acts 16:21 mentions customs not lawful for Romans, while Esther 3:8 highlights the diverse laws of a certain people, suggesting a tension between different legal systems.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 21, 24, 10, 3, 3, 'customs, which are not lawful', 'Customs and Their Worthlessness', 'This connection highlights the theme of customs being viewed negatively. Acts 16:21 refers to customs that are not lawful for Romans, while Jeremiah 10:3 emphasizes that the customs of the people are vain.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 21, 44, 16, 12, 12, 'being Romans', 'Roman Identity and Customs', 'Both passages emphasize the Roman identity of the citizens in Philippi. The mention of ''Romans'' in the source verse highlights the cultural context in which the events of the target passage occur.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 21, 44, 26, 3, 3, 'customs', 'Connection of Customs and Lawfulness', 'This connection highlights the theme of customs and their significance in both passages. In Acts 16:21, the focus is on customs deemed unlawful for Romans, while Acts 26:3 emphasizes expertise in Jewish customs, suggesting a contrast in cultural practices.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 22, 52, 2, 2, 2, NULL, 'Suffering and Boldness in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the suffering endured by Paul and his companions. Acts 16:22 describes their physical beating, while 1 Thessalonians 2:2 references their shameful treatment at Philippi, highlighting their boldness in continuing to preach despite adversity.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 22, 47, 6, 5, 5, NULL, 'Suffering and Persecution', 'Both passages emphasize suffering endured for faith. Acts 16:22 describes physical punishment, while 2 Corinthians 6:5 lists various forms of hardship, including ''stripes'' and ''tumults.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 22, 44, 22, 22, 26, 'the multitude rose up together against them', 'Violence Against Paul and Silas', 'Both passages emphasize the violent reactions against Paul and his companions. In Acts 16:22, the crowd rises up and commands to beat them, while in Acts 22:22, the crowd calls for Paul''s death and throws off their clothes, indicating a similar fervor for violence.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 22, 47, 11, 23, 25, 'commanded to beat them', 'Suffering for the Gospel', 'Both passages emphasize the physical suffering endured by Paul for the sake of spreading the Gospel. Acts 16:22 describes the beating of Paul and Silas, while 2 Corinthians 11:23-25 lists Paul''s numerous sufferings, including being beaten.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 22, 58, 11, 36, 36, NULL, 'Suffering and Persecution', 'Both passages emphasize the experience of suffering and physical punishment faced by believers. Acts 16:22 describes the beating of Paul and Silas, while Hebrews 11:36 mentions cruel mockings and scourgings endured by others.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 22, 40, 10, 17, 17, NULL, 'Persecution of Believers', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of persecution faced by believers. Acts 16:22 describes physical violence against Paul and Silas, while Matthew 10:17 warns of being delivered up and scourged.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 22, 40, 27, 26, 26, 'commanded to beat them', 'Connection of Violence and Punishment', 'Both passages emphasize the act of beating and scourging as forms of punishment inflicted by authorities. This connection highlights the theme of unjust suffering faced by individuals at the hands of the magistrates.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 23, 66, 2, 10, 10, 'cast them into prison', 'Suffering and Imprisonment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of suffering and imprisonment for believers. Acts 16:23 describes physical imprisonment, while Revelation 2:10 warns of future imprisonment as a trial for faith.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 23, 55, 2, 9, 9, NULL, 'Suffering and Imprisonment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize suffering and imprisonment. Acts 16:23 describes being cast into prison, while 2 Timothy 2:9 mentions suffering trouble and being in bonds, highlighting the theme of enduring hardship for the sake of the gospel.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 23, 9, 23, 22, 23, NULL, 'Prison and Pursuit Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of confinement and the pursuit of individuals. In Acts, Paul and Silas are imprisoned, while in 1 Samuel, David is being sought after and hidden from Saul.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 23, 40, 26, 48, 48, NULL, 'Connection of Betrayal and Imprisonment', 'Both passages emphasize the act of betrayal leading to confinement. In Acts, the apostles are imprisoned after being punished, while in Matthew, betrayal leads to Jesus being captured and held. This connection highlights the theme of betrayal resulting in imprisonment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 23, 40, 27, 63, 66, 'keep them safely', 'Imprisonment and Sealing', 'Both passages emphasize the act of securing something to prevent escape or deception. In Acts, the jailor is charged to keep the prisoners safely, while in Matthew, the sepulchre is made sure to prevent theft of Jesus'' body.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 23, 42, 21, 12, 12, NULL, 'Persecution and Imprisonment Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the experience of being imprisoned and persecuted for faith. Acts 16:23 describes the physical punishment and imprisonment of Paul and Silas, while Luke 21:12 foretells similar experiences for believers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 23, 44, 5, 18, 18, NULL, 'Imprisonment of Apostles', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of imprisonment of apostles for their actions. In Acts 16:23, Paul and Silas are cast into prison, while Acts 5:18 describes the apostles being put in prison.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 24, 18, 13, 27, 27, 'made their feet fast in the stocks', 'Connection of Imprisonment Imagery', 'This connection highlights the imagery of confinement in both passages. Acts describes physical imprisonment with ''made their feet fast in the stocks,'' while Job uses ''puttest my feet also in the stocks'' to express a sense of restriction.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 24, 18, 33, 11, 11, 'feet fast in the stocks', 'Connection of Imprisonment Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the imagery of confinement, with ''feet in the stocks'' symbolizing restriction and suffering. This connection highlights the theme of being trapped and the divine observation of one''s path.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 24, 24, 29, 26, 26, NULL, 'Imprisonment Motif in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the theme of imprisonment in both passages. Acts 16:24 describes physical imprisonment, while Jeremiah 29:26 discusses putting false prophets in prison and stocks.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 24, 24, 38, 26, 26, 'thrust them into the inner prison', 'Imprisonment and Plea for Mercy', 'This connection highlights the theme of imprisonment and the plea for mercy in both passages. In Acts, the imprisonment is physical, while in Jeremiah, the plea is for deliverance from a metaphorical imprisonment of death.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
